# Installer / CPharmSetup.exe — GitHub build reminder

When you change anything that affects **`CPharmSetup.exe`** or how it is shipped — including `wizard/**`, PyInstaller flags or bundled assets (`--add-data`, hidden imports, `build.bat` / spec inputs), or **`.github/workflows/build-wizard.yml`** — a **new Windows build for testing only comes from GitHub Actions** (`.github/workflows/build-wizard.yml`, PyInstaller on a Windows runner). **Local edits alone do not update GitHub artifacts or Releases.**

**Remind the user** (or follow yourself) to get a fresh test build:

1. **Commit** the change.
2. **Push** to GitHub (or run **Actions → `build-wizard` → Run workflow** / `workflow_dispatch` if the repo allows it).
3. **Verify** the workflow run completed successfully.
4. **Get the binary** from the run’s **Artifacts** (`CPharmSetup-exe-…`) or from **Releases**, depending on how the run was triggered.

Do not assume a local `pyinstaller` run replaces the need to confirm the CI build when the goal is testing the same bits users get from GitHub.

## Repo workflow (owner preference)

1. **`cursor-agent`** — Default branch for **Cursor/agent work**. Commit here and **`git push origin cursor-agent`** so Actions builds **`CPharmSetup.exe`** for testing. Do **not** use throwaway “sync” branches that only exist to open a PR.

2. **`main`** — Integration/release line. When the owner wants GitHub **Releases / default-branch builds** to match tested work, fast-forward or merge **`cursor-agent` → `main`** (`git checkout main && git merge cursor-agent && git push origin main`). No obligation to open a GitHub PR UI unless the owner wants review.

Routine agent commits: **branch `cursor-agent` → push → CI artifact → owner tests.** Promote to **`main`** when ready for the “official” line.
